<br>
/shrug<br>
<br>
I don't run around doing /guildstat on everyone, I assume they're part of the people they're hanging around with.  This is generally the case.  Kinda like Frawg training people in TOV on Vallon.  He ported over with SS, went in with SS, left with SS.  That pretty well defined it for me.<br>
<br>
And yes, the reason I didn't train people on Vallon was because causing XP loss was against the rules.  I don't see causing XP loss to be &quot;assholeish&quot; any more than I see shooting someone in the foot with a Quake rocketlauncher to be &quot;assholeish&quot;.  On Vallon I ddn't do it because it was against the rules, on Sullon it's just part of the game.  Pino himself didn't seem to be upset at all by it, so I hardly see what the fuss is about.  It's only &quot;griefing&quot; if the person you're doing it to feels grief, and Pino obviously doesn't.<br>
<br>
I dare say if the same thing happened to me, I wouldn't feel griefed either.  I knew the rules.  In Quake you have to accept spawncampers and guncampers, even though it's a type of gameplay designed to give them points at the expense of your gameplay, it's just part of the game.<br>
<br>
Are you going to let someone grab the rocketlauncher when you could stop them?  Just going to let them have it to be polite?  Are you going to let someone be level 59 when you have it in your power to make them level 54?<br>
<br>
I see it as the same thing.  It's a legal opportunity to weaken the enemy.  Pino died again last night, because someone landed snare on him.  The reason snare landed, no doubt, is because he was not level 59 anymore.<br>
<br>
This is just the way I play all games: to win.  &quot;Winning&quot; in EQ is a poorly defined term, but I dare say wiping 5 levels off of someone is a step in that direction.  Is it nice?  No.  Do you play games to be nice?  No.  If we're playing chess and I make a dumbass move that lets you take my queen, I expect you to take my queen, I would be vaguely irritated if you made another move just to be nice to me.<br>
<br>
I expect people to play to win, and to do things within the rules to accomplish that.<br>
