 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/ugrumples.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grumples</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>drunken' poon</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(10/4/01 12:48:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub73.ezboard.com/fsullonzektavernfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3914.topic&index=135>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: IE Defeats DB &amp; TDC, Ruin monk comments on PvP and D</span><hr size=1> And next time you're playing a nice game of chess with your buddy, and see the chance to checkmate, remember:  don't do it!  He's a human being!  If you checkmate his king, he'll be depressed.<br>
<br>
/scoff<br>
<br>
If we're gonna play, let's play.  I don't play games hoping the other person gives me &quot;breaks&quot; to be &quot;nice&quot;.  I expect mistakes to be taken full advantage of, I look for them to make mistakes that I can take advantage of.  That's the very definition of a game.<br>
<br>
As it turns out, EQ is one of the most drawn out games ever made, one that you'll spend months working on.  It's easy to come overly attached to it.  People have become so attached that minor setbacks like 3 unrezzable deaths in a row in POF makes them quit, or the server crashes and they lose a valuable and ultrarare piece of equipment that had just dropped 2 minutes prior, etc.<br>
<br>
As they say, it's just a game.  If you're so attached to the social aspect that you're willing to intentionally avoid trying to win, then why bother playing?  That's like suggesting the quarterback not try to fake a handoff, because the last time he did it they scored a touchdown and the other team was depressed they didn't get to tackle anyone.<br>
<br>
(You might play with intentional handicaps if you want a competitive game with someone who is simply not up to your skill level, e.g., as in golf, but I don't think that really applies here.)<br>
